 of reconversion, and demanding early prepara\ntions to protect tlie human victims of cutbacks and to gear our in\ndustrial and governmental machinery to a program of full employ\nmeat.\nAnd again, these warnings seems to have failbn\u2019on deaf fear's\nNo wage relief has y^t been furnished to the workers Whose\ntake-hom'e pa v is being cut by layoffs^ los's of overtime,1 down-grad\ning. etc. No effective plans have been made for re-employment and\nthe-orderly expansion of peacetime Production.\nAt a time like this, Congress lias actually decided to take a'{it'd1\nlonged vacation. It has left Washington without taking any actidii\non emergency unemployment benefits, on eliminating siiHst^ndafd\nwages, on adequate social security, or on legislation for full employ\nment. f\nBut now to labor s warnings have been added those of a nunv\nber of eminent Senators. \u20194T\u2019\nThe Mead war investigating committee has reported thafi\u2019uri\nless the government acts quickly, the United'States is heading for\nthe worst kind of postwar depression and Unemployment.\n\u201cShould the War in the Pacific end soon,\u201d S'eitat jrMe'ad WSVnS?,\nit will find us\u2019 largely utipfef>af\u2018ed'; to overcome our domestic pVdb\nlems. Reconversion will not have progressed\u2019far enough to absbrb;\nthe manpower which will be Suddenly released. Government wd\u2019rlr\nprograms will not Have been established* and unemployment on a\nlarge scale wilben^ue.\u201d\nIn the hearings on the Mu tray-Patman Full Employment. bill,\nSenatorsWagner and Murray have Issued similar warnings.\nEven enactment of this bill\u2019 ivill not make up. for the fact that\nCongress \"has done too little and'been too late in acting on matters\nof reconversion and postwar ecbhomic affairs,\" Wagner said, \u201cif\nwe fail to act promptly, we may once again be swept along the\nboom-and-bust road.\" v 1 h.\nMurray warned big business against flirting with ideas of a big\nsupply of cheap labor and opening the gates to \u201cpostwar enemy No.\n1.\u201d pointing to the British people\u2019s overwhelming defeat of tlieir\nreactionaries and tories.\nWhile Congress is on vacation, the CIO is urging adoption of\nthe Mead Committee\u2019s proposal that the Office of War Mobilization\nand Reconversion assume full powers to coordinate and direct the\nwork of all agencies concerned with reconversion.\nIt may also be p(#nted out that Congressional committees can\nget oti with their work even while Congress is :nbt hi session.\nBlit how about Congress itself' getting\u2019 back on th\u00a3 'joICbeftire\nOctober 1 and pushing through the big load\" of\u2019unfinished business\non which the immediate welfare of*our whole country depends?\nRussia\u2019s Challenge Te U* r-,\nRussia's principal postwar problem Is manpower1 slior'ta^e, \u2018Va:\nr Kuznot/.ov, a member of the Soviet !af>or misidon visiting th^\nsilly Kuznot/.ov, a member of the Soviet Ia(F>or mission visiting\nUnited States, said in Detroit. Tt was a surprising statement to\nworkers in that city, where fear of joblessness has resulted in mass\ndemonstration.\nKnznotzov also said flint the Russian government is retaining\nwartime take-home pay levels, though hours are being reduced to\n40 hours, and even less in dangerous occupations.\nThere in lies the challenge to opr American* type of enterprise.\nCan it.\" too. give it* people work,and yiconics sufficient to meet the\ncost (if a decent standard of'living after\u2018tW'war? Or will our stand\nard of living stagnate while that of Russia ri^ts? \"V\nIf ind,ustr>\\ Chambers of Commerce,* ntn'^piipetk\u2019diul Vithiers\nwho have been more concerned with baiting labor tlVin wR'H*,fWf&'\nvital problein, will join with AiiiVrica\u2019iv lalVdr'm firofnoti'ng li program\nof full employment after the war, this challenge etui be met success\nfully.\nUnt'ortiiuateiy many are hot thinking iu terms of lnccKtig the\nchallenge by making our deniocracy.'wo.rft put^in ierths bf shiipfeis\ntng unions,.with'some idea that? by desirOyihg theif puive^ to1 striVe\nfor better wages and working conditions the \"threait'v td profits will\nbe removed, 'yi/'\nRussia was grievonsly wounded bv the \\\\aiti tuvadejv 5\"ljhe was\nset hack in her effort to raise a, low standard, of living, lint despity\nthis handicap, by vCorkiug all her people she will he able to move\nforward toward a goal of decent housing, clothing and food for all\nher citizens.'\n'Americti is piMentiklly\u2019irt a position to move forward even more\nrapidly. 1 We cotild achieve irt a few years a standard, of living for\nall our Citizens such as to stagger the imagination. 'There need not\nbe 4 stum nor an underfed\u2019 jiers'On left in our nation, if we work in\npeace as We liavtf worked to wdh'tHe war. '1 ,J\u201c\nOnly ajieybn p ith little* faith in our system1 would deby this can\nbe done. \\e we have jftXt been warned by jjttnttW of \u2019ifturtd think\nii/g Yhaf >ve face the danger of mass unemployment and suffering.\nMeanwhile Congress goes home for a two-month vacation\n'frmj>loymehtTt'g>sl\u00ab\u2019\u2018t>on.\u2018 sib strting\nthe reactionaries and the fence-riders of Congress cannot ignore it.\nLEAVE WMC\n'r' (Contiirued from Page. One)\nmany Goodrich! 'Workers 'fate jobless\ndays if the 48-hour work-week is\nmaintained. Copies of the resolution\nwere Ordered \u2019sent\" to company and\ngovernment officials.\n\u2018Goodrich Local* members asked for\na shorter work-week fot Women1 em\nploy es\u2018several'weeks argo in- order to\nprevent more than 200 women being\nfo'rciti-to lr<se their jobs The Akron\nWNfC refused the request; atfd \u201cit is\nciet\u00bbfched ftiat it' also \"Will rCfitst the\nrequest fett- the 30-hour work-weik\u2014'\nafi act ttiit likely will resdlt ifjf the\nCl<)\u201c delegates Reaving the commis\nAL JACOBSON tD FOSTER\nAFL r CIO\nMembers, Labor Advisory Cdmmit.\nIk looks 'Tike fat'ionihg1 will soon *V\u00bb\novtfr, especially GA-SOLllVE. FUH! 1\nO